  pearls: ["When in doubt, sit them out: any suspected concussion requires removal from activity", "Loss of consciousness is NOT required for a concussion diagnosis; most concussions occur without LOC", "Worsening headache, repeated vomiting, increasing confusion, or seizure are red flags for intracranial hemorrhage", "Cognitive rest is as important as physical rest: limit screens, reading, and schoolwork", "Return to activity must be graduated: rest, light activity, sport-specific exercise, non-contact drills, full contact, full competition", "Second impact syndrome: a second concussion before recovery from the first can cause fatal cerebral edema"],
  lifespan: { title: "Across the Lifespan", content: "Children and adolescents typically take longer to recover from concussion than adults (2-4 weeks vs. 7-10 days) and are more vulnerable to second impact syndrome. In young children, concussion symptoms may present as increased crying, changes in eating or sleeping, loss of interest in favorite activities, and unsteady walking. In elderly patients, concussions are often caused by falls and may be complicated by anticoagulant use, which increases the risk of intracranial hemorrhage. Elderly patients should have a lower threshold for CT imaging." },
